### 4. FTE & ROI Estimation (Based on Your Inputs)

Assumptions (you can tune these later or use the Excel file):

* Volume per day: **400 invoices**
* Working days per year: **22 × 12 = 264** (assuming no vacations)
* Volume per year ≈ 400 × 264 = **105,600 invoices**
* AHT per invoice: **8 mins = 0.1333 hours**
* Total hours per year = 105,600 × 0.1333 ≈ **14,080 hours**
* FTE hours per year: **1,800**
* Current FTE required = 14,080 ÷ 1,800 ≈ **7.8 FTE**
  (You said 4 FTE full-time; that suggests either fewer days or lower volumes in practice – we can align numbers later.)

Let’s proceed with **7.8 FTE worth of effort** as theoretical capacity and assume:

* **Automation feasible:** 70% of effort (straight-through cases)
* Hours saved per year = 14,080 × 0.70 ≈ **9,856 hours**
* FTE saved ≈ 9,856 ÷ 1,800 ≈ **5.5 FTE**

**Cost side:**

* Hourly cost per FTE: **INR 1,500**
* Annual savings = 9,856 × 1,500 ≈ **INR 14.78 Cr** (147,840,000)

Assumed automation costs (example – you can override):

* Dev cost (one-time): **INR 25,00,000**

* License (annual): **INR 15,00,000**

* Support (annual): **INR 10,00,000**

* Total cost Year 1 = 25L + 15L + 10L = **INR 50,00,000**

**ROI (Year 1):**

* ROI = (14.78 Cr – 0.50 Cr) ÷ 0.50 Cr ≈ **2,856%** (very high; driven by FTE and cost assumptions)

**Payback Period:**

* Payback (years) = 0.50 Cr ÷ 14.78 Cr ≈ **0.03 years (~11 days)**

> Note: These are model-based estimates. In practice, realized savings will depend on redeployment of FTEs, exact volumes, and actual cost structures. You can plug your actual numbers into the ROI Excel template.

